  "prompt": "What are bit vectors?",
  "response": "Bit vectors are a data structure used to compactly represent a sequence of bits, where each bit can be independently set, cleared, or tested. They are useful in various applications, especially when memory efficiency is a concern. Let's explore bit vectors in more detail:\n\n1. Definition:\n   A bit vector is essentially an array of bits. Each element in the array can be either 0 or 1.\n\n2. Implementation:\n   Bit vectors are typically implemented using:\n   - Arrays of integers (where each integer holds multiple bits)\n   - Specialized bit manipulation libraries\n   - Custom classes that manage memory at the bit level\n\n3. Key operations:\n   - Set: Set a specific bit to 1\n   - Clear: Set a specific bit to 0\n   - Test: Check the value of a specific bit\n   - Count: Count the number of set bits (1s)\n   - Find first/last set: Find the position of the first or last set bit\n\n4. Advantages:\n   - Memory efficiency: Bit vectors can store a large amount of data in a small space\n   - Fast operations: Bitwise operations are typically very fast at the hardware level\n   - Useful for set operations: They can be used to represent sets efficiently\n\n5. Common use cases:\n   - Bit flags: Representing multiple boolean flags in a single integer\n   - Bloom filters: Probabilistic data structures for membership testing\n   - Sparse data representation: Efficiently storing large amounts of binary data\n   - Graph algorithms: Representing adjacency matrices or sets of vertices\n\n6. Limitations:\n   - Limited to binary data: Only two values (0 and 1) can be stored in each position\n   - Can be less intuitive: Working with bits directly requires understanding bitwise operations\n\nTo illustrate a simple bit vector implementation in Python, here's an example:\n\n```python\nclass BitVector:\n    def __init__(self, size):\n        \"\"\"\n        Initialize a bit vector of the given size.\n        \n        :param size: The number of bits in the vector\n        \"\"\"\n        self.size = size\n        # Use an integer array to store the bits, where each integer represents 32 bits\n        self.data = [0] * ((size + 31) // 32)\n\n    def set(self, index):\n        \"\"\"\n        Set the bit at the given index to 1.\n        \n        :param index: The index of the bit to set\n        \"\"\"\n        if 0 <= index < self.size:\n            word_index = index // 32\n            bit_index = index % 32\n            self.data[word_index] |= (1 << bit_index)\n\n    def clear(self, index):\n        \"\"\"\n        Clear the bit at the given index (set it to 0).\n        \n        :param index: The index of the bit to clear\n        \"\"\"\n        if 0 <= index < self.size:\n            word_index = index // 32\n            bit_index = index % 32\n            self.data[word_index] &= ~(1 << bit_index)\n\n    def test(self, index):\n        \"\"\"\n        Test the bit at the given index.\n        \n        :param index: The index of the bit to test\n        :return: True if the bit is set, False otherwise\n        \"\"\"\n        if 0 <= index < self.size:\n            word_index = index // 32\n            bit_index = index % 32\n            return bool(self.data[word_index] & (1 << bit_index))\n        return False\n\n    def count(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Count the number of set bits in the vector.\n        \n        :return: The number of set bits\n        \"\"\"\n        count = 0\n        for word in self.data:\n            count += bin(word).count('1')\n        return count\n\n# Example usage\nbv = BitVector(100)\nbv.set(0)\nbv.set(50)\nbv.set(99)\n\nprint(bv.test(0))  # True\nprint(bv.test(1))  # False\nprint(bv.test(50)) # True\nprint(bv.count())  # 3\n```\n\nThis implementation demonstrates a basic bit vector with set, clear, test, and count operations. It uses an array of integers to store the bits, where each integer represents 32 bits. This approach is memory-efficient and allows for fast bit manipulation operations.",
